{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600050"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:00:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:00:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15601"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15601"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.1,0.55,0,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66627"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8292"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52081"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"577"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7005"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8189"},{"type":"tags","id":"8193"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"8222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20016"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20019"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22235"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66627"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her thyroid condition. She has a medical history of hypothyroidism treated with thyroxine. She does not take any other regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her thyroid is diffusely enlarged but non-tender with no palpable nodules. Thyroid function tests reveal thyroid stimulating hormone 2.1 mU/L (0.4-4.0) and free thyroxine 16 pmol/L (9-19).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following thyroid conditions requires thyroidectomy as the only management option?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hashimoto thyroiditis","Graves\u0027 disease","Toxic multinodular goitre","Solitary thyroid nodule","Papillary thyroid cancer"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAmong thyroid conditions, \u003Cstrong\u003Epapillary thyroid cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is the only condition that definitively requires surgical management with total thyroidectomy (with or without lymph node dissection depending on staging). Small papillary tumours can be treated more conservatively and some incidentally found tumours (\u0026lt; 1cm) could be kept under observation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile other thyroid conditions may eventually require surgery, they all have alternative management options that should be considered first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraves\u0027 disease\u003C/strong\u003E can be managed with three different approaches: antithyroid medications (such as carbimazole or propylthiouracil), radioactive iodine ablation, or thyroidectomy. The choice depends on factors including patient preference, disease severity, and local expertise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic multinodular goitre\u003C/strong\u003E can be managed with antithyroid medications for symptom control, radioactive iodine for definitive treatment, or surgery if there are compressive symptoms or concern for malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHashimoto thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily managed with thyroid hormone replacement therapy. Surgery is rarely indicated unless there are compressive symptoms from goitre or concern for lymphoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESolitary thyroid nodules\u003C/strong\u003E require fine needle aspiration if they meet size criteria or have suspicious features on ultrasound. Most are benign and can be monitored with serial ultrasound. Surgery is only indicated if fine needle aspiration shows malignancy or if there are compressive symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in thyroid disease management is that most conditions have multiple treatment options, and the choice depends on individual patient factors, disease characteristics, and patient preferences. Only thyroid cancer mandates surgical management as the primary treatment modality.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Total thyroidectomy is the definitive treatment for thyroid cancer, but other thyroid conditions often have medical management options.","Graves\u0027 disease can be managed with antithyroid medications, radioactive iodine, or surgery depending on patient factors.","Most thyroid nodules do not require surgery unless there are concerning features or compressive symptoms."],"references":["Shah JP. Thyroid carcinoma: epidemiology, histology, and diagnosis. Clin Adv Hematol Oncol. 2015 Apr;13(4 Suppl 4):3-6. PMID: 26430868; PMCID: PMC5526593","Kitahara CM, Schneider AB. Epidemiology of Thyroid Cancer. Cancer Epidemiol Biomarkers Prev. 2022 Jul 1;31(7):1284-1297. doi: 10.1158/1055-9965.EPI-21-1440. PMID: 35775227; PMCID: PMC9473679","Boucai L, Zafereo M, Cabanillas ME. Thyroid Cancer: A Review. JAMA. 2024 Feb 6;331(5):425-435. doi: 10.1001/jama.2023.26348. PMID: 38319329","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15601"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52081"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T17:27:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T17:27:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8292"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66627"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"e